observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our recommendation and management agreed that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

GAD Focal Person to (i) submit the endorsed Annual GPB within the time prescribed under Item V of COA Circular No. 2014-001; (ii) include in the Annual Accomplishment Report all changes in the PPAs due to supplemental budgets to reflect the correct accomplishment/performance of the Municipality for the year and for proper monitoring and evaluation by the oversight agencies; (iii) make sure that the GPB and Report and their supporting documents are properly prepared; (iv) inform in writing the DILG Office of the changes in the DILG endorsed GPB and/or if there is a need to implement additional PPAs relevant to current gender issues or GAD related undertakings and adjust the GPB to cater the changes pursuant to Item 6.0.C.7.2 of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01; 


GPFS and the Municipal Budget Officer be guided by Item 4.1.C.4 of JMC No. 2013-01 as amended by Item 3.0.C.4 of  JMC No. 2016-01 in the attributions of LGU programs and projects to the GAD Budget;

MPDC spearhead the setting up and maintenance of the GAD database to serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation;

GFPS to (i) provide technical assistance in the implementation of the GPB and monitor its implementation so that optimal utilization of the fund could be achieved for the benefits of the intended beneficiaries pursuant to Section 6.1 of the  JMC No. 2016-01; and (ii) regularly monitor if the GAD budget is being spent for what it was intended for and check on the actual cost of implementing the GAD activities;

BAC to be guided by COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009 in the submission of contract/purchase order and the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 in the procurement of goods and services; 


Municipal Accountant, as the internal auditor, to see to it that supporting documents attached to disbursement vouchers are accurate and complete before processing of claims pursuant to Section 474 b (5) of R.A. No. 7160 and Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445; and

Municipal Budget Officer to reflect in the Obligation Requests the specific GAD PPAs for each disbursement was charged for proper evaluation of the amount expended per PPA.

We recommended and management agreed that the Municipal Mayor require the:

Inventory Committee to conduct the complete physical count of all inventories and property, plant and equipment (PPEs) in accordance with Section 124 of Volume I of Manual on NGAS for LGUs and submit the corresponding RPCI and RCPPE to the Audit Team within the timeframe provided by the same regulation; 


Concerned office to exert extra effort to dig-up records of the issuance of the medicines and distribution of the agricultural produce and agricultural and marine supplies for the proper adjustment of financial records of the Municipality;

Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant to (i) exert efforts in tracing the “items in transit” and properly classify the inventories and PPEs in its proper accounts; and (ii) always reconcile the result of the count with the property records and accounting records;

Concerned accountable officer/office to explain for the “unlocated” properties and render an account for those properties pursuant to Section 494 of the GAAM; and  



Municipal Treasurer to make a report of unserviceable/non-functional PPEs in the IIRUP which could be undertaken simultaneously with the physical inventory for disposal and eventual proper relief of accountabilities.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (LDRRMO) to (i) properly reflect/incorporate the Quick Response Fund (QRF) and the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years to the LDRRMFIP; and (ii) properly classify the expenditures in the LDRRMFIP and make sure that classification are reconciled with other reports;

Municipal Accountant to strictly adhere with the guidelines set forth by (i) COA Circular No. 2012-002 for proper accounting and recording of the utilization of the LDRRM Fund; (ii) COA Circular No. 2015-009 in the proper recording of transactions in accordance with International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS); and (iii) Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445, Section 474 b (5) of R.A. No. 7160 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 for proper documentation of transactions;   


Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to strictly adhere to the requirements of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and Item 8.0 of the Administrative Order No. 233 series of 2008 on the procurement of goods and services specifically of Motor Vehicles; and 



Municipal Engineer to be guided by the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013 in providing information to the public relative to the programs/projects/activities of the Municipality.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

GAD Focal Person to (i) submit the endorsed Annual GPB within the time prescribed under Item V of COA Circular No. 2014-001; (ii) include in the Annual Accomplishment Report all changes in the projects/programs/activities (PPAs) due to supplemental budgets to reflect the correct accomplishment/performance of the Municipality for the year and for proper monitoring and evaluation by the oversight agencies; (iii) make sure that the Report and its supporting documents are properly prepared in accordance with the provisions of Section 4.1.C.8 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 and the amendments in Section 7.0 of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01; and (iv) inform in writing the DILG Office of the changes in the DILG endorsed GPB and/or if there is a need to implement additional PPAs relevant to current gender issues or GAD related undertakings and adjust the GPB to cater the changes pursuant to Section 6.0 (2) of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01;

GAD Focal Point System (GPFS) and the Municipal Budget Officer be guided by Item 4.1.C.4 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 as amended by Item 3.0.C.4 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01 in the attributions of LGU programs and projects to the GAD Budget;

Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) spearhead the setting up and maintenance of the GAD database to serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation;

GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) to provide technical assistance in the implementation of the GAD Plan and Budget (GPB) and monitor its implementation so that optimal utilization of the fund could be achieved for the benefits of the intended beneficiaries pursuant to Section 6.1 of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01;

Bids and Awards Committee to be guided by COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009 in the submission of contract/purchase order and the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 in the procurement of goods and services; 

Municipal Accountant, as the internal auditor, to see to it that supporting documents attached to disbursement vouchers are accurate and complete before processing claims pursuant to Section 474 b (5) of R.A. No. 7160 and Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445; and

Municipal Budget Officer to reflect in the Obligation Requests the specific GAD PPAs each disbursements was charged for proper evaluation of the amount expended per PPA.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
BAC (i) to submit plausible explanations for all the deficiencies noted and lacking supporting documents to arrive at a decision in audit;   (ii) henceforth, determine the proper mode of procurement to be used for the procurement activity of the Municipality to streamline the process and to prepare the required supporting documents; and     (iii) strictly comply with the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 on the procurement of infrastructure projects with regards to procurement planning, invitation to observers, and posting requirement, among others, to enhance transparency and establish regularity of the procurement process and award of contracts;
Head of the Accounting Office to check the adequacy, propriety and completeness of supporting documents prescribed under Sections 9.1 and 9.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 before processing claims for payments to ensure compliance with the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and to establish the legality, validity and propriety of the disbursements;
Municipal Treasurer to issue PAR to the end-user of the ambulance and rescue vehicles for proper accountability thereof; and
Municipal Engineer (i) to conduct a thorough detailed engineering on infrastructure projects implemented by the Municipality pursuant to Annex A of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; and (ii) be guided by DPWH DO No. 197, series of 2016 in the preparation of ABC.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (LDRRMO) to (i) prepare the LDRRMFIP in accordance with the format prescribed in Annex A of COA Circular No. 2012-002.  It should also include the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years; (ii) strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular 2012-002 in the utilization of the LDRRM Fund; (iii) consider increasing the appropriation intended for the acquisition of DRRM equipage in the LDRRMF Plan and prioritize the acquisition of the lacking DRRM equipment, tools and paraphernalia to comply with the minimum standard pursuant to DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2012-73.  This is to complement the existing equipage already available in the MDRRM Office; (iv) consider the requisitions of items needed to maintain pre-positioned food packs and hygiene kits for at least 500 families at any given time in compliance with the minimum standards and pursuant to NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2013-1; and (v) consider that storage/warehouse is established to properly safeguard the supplies, materials, equipment and relief goods of the DRRM Office against loss and wastage through illegal or improper disposition pursuant to Item VI of COA Circular No. 2014-002;

Municipal Accountant and LDRRMO to (i) prepare and submit the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF to the Audit Team in accordance with Item 5.1.5 of COA Circular No. 2012-002; and (ii) submit the List of DRRM Equipment Procured out of Local Appropriation Ordinance and Cash Donations/Donated PPE Received as of December 31, 2019.

Municipal Accountant to strictly adhere with the guidelines set forth by (i) COA Circular No. 2012-002 for proper accounting and recording of the utilization of the LDRRM Fund and transfer of unexpended LDRRM Fund to Special Trust Fund; (ii) COA Circular No. 2015-009 in the proper recording of transactions in accordance with International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS); and (iii) Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 for proper documentation of transactions; 

Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to strictly adhere to the requirements of (i) Annex H of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 on the procurement of goods and services thru Small Value Procurement; and (ii) COA Circular No. 2009-001 in the submission of contracts/purchase orders executed/issued by the Municipality; and 

Municipal Engineer to (i) be guided by the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013 in providing information to the public relative to the programs/projects/activities of the Municipality; and (ii) ensure that the CARI is timely posted by the contractor in order to properly serve its purpose.

We recommended the following:

The Municipal Mayor along with the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator and Municipal Engineer strictly follow the provisions of DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1 in planning the programs/projects/activities funded by 20% Development Fund and their implementation.  Ensure that these programs/projects/activities partake the nature of investment or capital expenditures that will contribute to the attainment of socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes of the Municipality.  See to it also that those development projects identified in the AIP are fully implemented for the benefit of the constituents; 

The Bids and Awards Committee observe strictly the (i) provisions of Section 48.3 and Item 8.b.ii of Annex H of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 in the procurement of goods and services; and (ii) COA Circular No. 2009-001 in the submission of contracts/purchase orders executed/issued by the municipality.  Moreover, submit the lacking documents cited above to the Audit Team to comply with the requirements of the IRR and address the deficiencies noted;

The Municipal Accountant (i) be guided by the requirements of Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445, COA Circular No. 2012-001 and Section 474 b(5) of R.A. No. 7160 for proper documentation of claims against government funds; and (ii) submit the lacking documents mentioned above; and

The Municipal Engineer (i) be guided by the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013 in providing information to the public relative to the programs/projects/activities of the Municipality; and (ii) ensure that the CARI is timely posted by the contractor in order to properly serve its purpose.

